  "chunk_index": 23,
  "summary": "While walking in the garden, Poirot is approached by a tense Mrs. Rundell. She questions his motives for being in Broadchurch, suggesting that his stated reason—investigating the death of Mrs. McGinty—is merely a convenient excuse. She also inquires about an anonymous letter, which she dismisses as a cowardly fabrication. Her reaction leaves Poirot wondering if she is attempting to mislead him or if she is actually Lily Garfield, a woman recently seen in a photograph and known to have undergone shorthand training.\n\nLater, Poirot experiences a sudden intuition regarding the murder weapon. While at the Long Grass Hotel, he discovers a brass object on a bookshelf. Molly enters and identifies the object as a \"sugar hammer\" or \"sugar mallet,\" a heavy, axe-shaped item decorated with colored stones and a bird with emerald eyes. Molly, who purchased it at a charity sale featuring items from the Wetherbys, jokingly refers to it as a \"wife's best friend\" for killing a husband. Poirot notices a faint stain on the blade of the hammer. Believing it to be the murder weapon, he wraps it in paper and hides it in a box in his bedroom before leaving the house.\n\nIn a separate scene at Golden Plover Manor, Mrs. Oliver and Robin Upward discuss a character Mrs. Oliver has created. Mrs. Oliver expresses frustration with the character's traits, specifically his identity as a Finnish vegetarian.",
